2.3 Impossibility of oscillations
Impossible to reverse directions and move back and forth
That is under autonomous system if your particle starts at positive velocity,
it cannot never reach negative velocity. The velocity function f is smooth so to
go from positive to negative, you must rst reach f(x) = 0. This is ne if our
velocity function is a function of time like f(t, x) so it is possible for the parti-
cle to go from 0 to negative velocity. However, in autonomous system velocity
strictly depends on position, so once the particle is approaching the position of
0 velocity (xed point), it will never have the velocity to move past that xed
point to attain a negative velocity.
However, this does not hold for, say, 2-D system. The particle can indeed
moves in a circle. Think of it as bending and looping the real line back into a
circle.
One example where this autonomous rule velocity only depends on posi-
tion not time makes sense is in population. Now position x is the current
population size, and velocity f(x) is the growth rate. Then, if we reach a xed
point of x = 0 where f (x) = 0, then x will be 0 forever. There is no people
alive to reproduce so no matter how long we wait, the population size is still zero.
The dynamics of autonomous 1 D is very limited.
1. Either x(t) goes to
2. Or x(t) approaches a xed point
2.4 Bifurcations
The system depends on some parameter r. Bifurcation is when changing r
changes the qualitative nature of the solution trajectory x(t).

8.1 Index of a closed curve C
Imagine putting a closed region into a vector eld. The vector eld rotates
continuously (not too disruptively change orientation). Imagine a rod moving
around the curve for one full loop. The index of the curve is the net rotation
of the rod. Positive if the rod rotates counter-clockwise as we move counter-
clockwise (that is the rod movement and its rotation has the same orientation),
and negative if the rod rotates clockwise as we move counter-clockwise around
the closed curve.
Properties of index:

have many choices: it can either converge, diverge to our closed orbit or form a
closed orbit of its own. The rst two choices lead to a limit cycle.

line is unstable and solid is stable.

Theorem 12.1 (Deciency Zero Theorem). Given a network with nite set of
species S and deciency 0, we have
1. If network not weakly reversible and all rate constants are positive, then
the sysem cannot have a periodic solution.
2. If the network is weakly reversible and all rate constants are positive, there
is exactly one equilibrium solution which is locally asymptotically sta-
ble.
